%page

The Inherent Weaknesses


	Often unprotected in storage and transmission

	Too many to remember

	Foolish password policies

	People are untrained in creating and storing them

	All passwords are ultimately breakable


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Passwords Have Certain Advantages


	You can often control how strong they are

	More people are acquiring better password habits

	Your memory is (still) a relatively safe container


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

The Three Factors of Authentication


	What you know
		passwords

	What you have
		digital or physical keys, identification

	What you are
		biometrics: fingerprints, iris scans

		Don't necessarily compromise identity
		Not easy to steal or copy like an ID or fingerprint
		Can't physically lose it if stored in your brain

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%page

Strong Unique Passwords Matter


	Often quickest backdoor into systems
		for account access
		privilege escalation

	All passwords ultimately breakable with enough time, resources
		if not today or tomorrow, then in ten years

	Strong means higher cost: Adversary's time, resources, frustration

	Don't be low-hanging fruit

